## Objective
- Read SPEC.md and continue building the gridcalc-xl spreadsheet engine project until complete, running tests with `pytest -q`

## Important Details
- SPEC.md defines a pure-logic Python library with one public class `Workbook` providing multi-sheet spreadsheet engine with integer/string formula semantics, absolute references, copy, named ranges, undo/redo, persistence, and incremental recomputation
- Grid is A1-Z99 (26 columns × 99 rows = 2574 cells max)
- No deletion APIs, no floats, no escape sequences in strings, no case-insensitive parsing
- Formula results are always int, str, or error string (never None)
- Incremental recomputation is behaviorally observable through `eval_count` property
- Persistence is string-based (JSON round-trip)

## Work State
### Completed
- Fixed cache invalidation in `sheet.py` set() method to invalidate dependent cells' caches
- Added `_invalidate_caches_for_cell()` method to `workbook.py` for R10 incremental recomputation
- Fixed test assertions in `test_gridcalc.py` that incorrectly expected formula text from `get()` instead of evaluated values
- Fixed `test_r17_copy_out_of_grid` to properly test out-of-grid reference scenario
- All 61 tests passing with `pytest -q`
- Verified R10, R17, R19-R20, R24-R25, R26-R27 with manual tests

### Active
- Testing R12 size bounds with 256-cell chain (16×16 grid A1:P16)
- Hit recursion error in evaluator when evaluating deep formula chains

### Blocked
- Recursion error in `evaluator.py` when testing 256-cell chain - likely due to cycle detection or stack overflow in `_ev_ref` → `_get_cell_keyed` → `_eval_formula` → `_ev` call chain

## Next Move
1. Investigate recursion error in evaluator for deep chains - check if cycle detection is incorrectly triggering or if recursion limit needs adjustment
2. Fix evaluator to handle deep chains without recursion errors while maintaining correctness

